{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.2,0.02,0.01,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52536"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of cramping left-sided abdominal pain. The pain starts in his flank and radiates down into his scrotum. He has never had these symptoms before. He has a medical history of impaired glucose tolerance and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications include metformin and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft to palpation. Urinalysis shows haemoglobin +++. CT scan reveals a 6 mm stone at the lower end of the left ureter with mild left hydronephrosis, and a small stone in the right renal pelvis (Image 1). Bloods are taken for laboratory analysis (Image 2). Intramuscular diclofenac is given, and the patient is kept under observation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest indication for urgent surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ongoing intractable pain despite optimal medical management","CT findings of a 6 mm ureteric stone","Haematuria on urinalysis","Soft abdomen on palpation","Fever and tachycardia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of renal colic, the patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Efever and tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E are the strongest indicators for urgent surgical intervention. These vital signs suggest an early septic process secondary to urinary obstruction, which requires prompt decompression of the urinary system. A ureteric stent would achieve this, relieving pressure on the kidneys and assisting in clearing the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOngoing intractable pain\u003C/strong\u003E despite optimal medical management can be an indication for intervention, but it is not as urgent as signs of developing sepsis. In this case, the patient has only recently received analgesia, so ongoing pain assessment would be needed to determine if this becomes an issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ECT findings\u003C/strong\u003E of a 6 mm ureteric stone are significant but not necessarily an immediate indication for surgery. Stones up to 7 mm may pass spontaneously, though with increasing difficulty as size increases. The presence of hydronephrosis adds to the clinical picture but doesn\u0027t necessitate immediate intervention in the absence of other concerning factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaematuria\u003C/strong\u003E on urinalysis is a common finding in renal colic and, while supportive of the diagnosis, does not on its own indicate a need for urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esoft abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E on palpation is actually a reassuring sign, as it suggests no peritoneal involvement or other abdominal pathology. This finding would not indicate a need for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther indications for surgical intervention in renal colic include renal angle tenderness, single kidney, or impaired renal function. Patients without these urgent indications can often be managed medically with analgesia, high oral fluid intake, and possibly alpha-blockers, while monitoring for stone passage. However, when signs of sepsis are present, as in this case, urgent urological consultation and surgical management are necessary to prevent potentially life-threatening complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clear evidence of sepsis in a patient with renal calculus disease is an indication for urgent active intervention.","Fever and tachycardia in a patient with renal colic suggest early urosepsis and require prompt decompression of the urinary system."],"references":["Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Australian Family Physician. 2017; 46:9 (648-652). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/september/urolithiasis","Zumstein V, Beschert P, Abt D, Schmid HP, Panne CM, Putora PM. Surgical management of urolithiasis \u2013 a systematic analysis of available guidelines. BMC Urol. 2018;18(25). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5894235/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18578"},{"type":"media","id":"18579"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18578"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c6836c5-6003-41ff-baa7-3f64a30f60df.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c6836c5-6003-41ff-baa7-3f64a30f60df.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":575,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18579"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9552d79b-0f71-472e-8dd3-2611337018c6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9552d79b-0f71-472e-8dd3-2611337018c6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":329}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-06T14:27:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T14:28:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"695"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52536"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",